      <description>&lt;DIV&gt;&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
Sharbreena wrote:&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;DIV&gt;While that would technically work Ex, I think codeing that would be beyond current technology.&lt;/DIV&gt;&lt;BR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;HR&gt;&#xD;
&lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;&lt;BR&gt;Would have to be done with instance's more then likely, if possible at all today. No idea though, out of my league.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;The important thing is to note that the game is fun, when your achieving more then one more AA. &lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;In my opinion, there should be alternate way's of doing several things. For experience/AA or regular, there should be plenty of search and destroy type quest's, and or just zone's that need to be "tamed" so to speak. They might not give you anything you can use, outside of a twink item here and there, but the experience and challenge of the zone should be good, and cover quite a bit of level's, from casual to high end content. &lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;I remember levelling up, place's like Najena, befallen, the Common's, all had a great variety of level's. Later Sol A, probably Crushbone (never really got into it though), Paludal as well... you could find at least 10 level's of experience in these zones, from the time you could survive zoning in. Later Sol B, VT, Luclin zone's, and even later POP zone's... All gave you a ton of different level's and people from different progressional point's could just go to different spots in the zone's, and have great experience (for that time period). &lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Now it seem's that everytime a new expansion is brought out, there is no reason to go back to the last one's, for anyone really. Outside of a quest here and there.&amp;nbsp; If you can survive the initial zone's of the expansion, then ussually, your good to go for the rest of it, if you just gear yourself as you go, Casual or Raider.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Then there should be the zone's like UP (Using old school zone's as an example), where you can check for name's, round up some guildie's, and go work on them. Not just raid mob's that only raider's can handle, I mean the one's like old day's, where a group of people from all aspects of the game, could come together and kill these things, for the bragging right's as well as the /random 100 Loot Right's. Mob's that are do-able, but not necessarily farmable (no-trade/drop item's, level required). Where if your beyond that point in progression, your not going to be really into killing it, unless you just like ruining things for other's (Or you want to help them).&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Finally, the questing and unlocking content, the stuff for both casual and Raider alike. They could have probably easily fixed alot of the itemization problem with quest/flag trivial stuff, if the experience of doing it was valuable... Maybe a certain amount of experience, which you determine if AA or not. If the tasks gave everyone a couple of AA's at the end, they probably wouldn't mind doing them as much. Time vs Reward anymore, not Risk vs. Reward.&lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;Unfortunately for me, the game has hit me as being very repetitive, and I have lost interest in alot of aspects of play. Seem's like the more stuff that come's up, the weaker the last content become's in spades. It's unfortunate all the way around, for everyone. Sound's like the doing over and over again of thing's that casual's do (farming for armor quests, certain ingrediant's, bassically, killing the same stuff day after day after day), are hitting the high end as well... &lt;/P&gt;&#xD;
&lt;P&gt;All thing's could be changed to make the game more fun, and a little bit harder probably as well. However, this is not the route they have been going, for a while now. Seem's to sound like the progression this time around, was purposely made to take alot more time, rather then skill, to get through. &lt;/P&gt;</description>
